  "prompt": "When you look at yourself in the mirror, is the reality of what other people see greater or worse than what you see?",
  "response": "When you look at yourself in the mirror, the image you see is a reversed version of your face, which is not how others see you. People see you as you truly are, not mirrored. This difference can lead to some interesting psychological effects:\n\n1. **Familiarity Bias**: You are more accustomed to seeing your mirrored image, so you might perceive it as more \"correct\" or appealing. When you see a non-mirrored photo or video of yourself, it might feel slightly off or less flattering because it\u2019s not what you\u2019re used to.\n   \n2. **Aesthetic Perception**: Some studies suggest that people tend to find their mirrored image more attractive than their true image because of their familiarity with it. However, this doesn\u2019t mean others see you as worse\u2014just differently.\n\n3. **Social Perception**: How others perceive you goes beyond just physical appearance. It includes your expressions, body language, and how you present yourself in real life, which a mirror can\u2019t fully capture.\n\nIn essence, the reality of what others see isn\u2019t necessarily greater or worse\u2014it\u2019s just different. Your perspective is shaped by the mirror\u2019s reversal and your own self-perception, while others see you in a more objective, unaltered way. Beauty and perception are subjective, so what matters most is how you feel about yourself, not just how others see you.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
